Revisiting the tour leaves me speechless the way we had each other—you all showed up for music and art in a big way, and with a level of excitement and freedom that I will never forget. Stadium after stadium. Sold out crowds. The deafening singalongs.

Chromatica was colorful revenge. The chaos of it all became pure energy and life. With a texture best experienced live.

"STRUT IT OUT, WALK A MILE

Self-acceptance is a theme that cuts through all my songs. I believe it is always possible to dig deep and find your greatness. Self-discovery is an art. Self-love is a practice.

I love you monsters more than I can say. In a stadium filled with YOU it came to life. Thank you for that feeling 🙏 🖤 I hope you will feel seen when you watch this film. And know that I edited it carefully to honor you.

Webb Telescope: supernova discovery machine! 

Webb has identified 10 times more supernovae in the early universe than previously known. Several are the most distant examples of their type, including those used to measure the universe's expansion rate: https://t.co/WOj3cTOpHw https://t.co/LyqZcjYRGj

tweet_1800246280666427635.user_comment: Webb uncovered ~80 supernovae in a patch of sky the thickness of a grain of rice held at arm’s length. This included several Type Ia supernovae, which are so predictably bright that they are used as a standard to measure distances and calculate the universe's expansion rate.

tweet_1800246282293797065.user_comment: Scientists expect ancient supernovae to contain far fewer heavy chemical elements than Sun-like stars. Comparing these supernovae with those nearby will help us form a more accurate view of star formation and supernovae explosion mechanisms in the early universe.

tweet_1798780060645593481.user_comment:
Tiny star, big potential.

Webb studied the planet-forming disk around a star weighing 1/10th of our Sun, finding it holds the largest number of carbon-containing molecules seen to date in such a disk: https://t.co/qtlgVjcXQi

What this tells us about potential future planets ⬇️ https://t.co/NboXyzLEpX

tweet_1798780076500332658.user_comment: The star, ISO-Chal 147, is just one to two million years old. The 13 different carbon-bearing molecules Webb detected within its planet-forming disk include the first detection of ethane outside of our solar system, as well as ethylene, propyne, and more. https://t.co/MUg7f3k4x6

tweet_1798780079893565689.user_comment: With so much gaseous carbon in the disk, there is likely little carbon left in the solid materials that planets would form from, making them carbon-poor. The team plans to expand their study to further understand how common carbon-rich, rocky planet-forming zones are.
